<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-120-083 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 936 670</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  July 1991 v9 n7 p238(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>On site: the tamperproof office. (includes related article onidentifying the risks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>LaPlante, Alice.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sun Life Assurance Co of Canada, an international insurancecompany in Toronto, does everything it can to keep its data securesince company officials feel the worst thing that could happenwould be to lose credibility with their clients.andP;  The company hasidentified security threats and has developed a three-prongedstrategy to deal with these potential threats.andP;  The first prong isto recommend software tools that can protect sensitive files fromunauthorized access and computer viruses.andP;  Another prong is aclassifying system and an appropriate security plan for eachclass: highest for the most confidential data, midlevel for datathat, if lost, would be inconvenient but not a real detriment, andlow-level for department and personal files.andP;  Protective measuresagainst viruses include a change management process that includesViruScan from McAfee Associates that is used any time a change ismade in the system.andP;  The third prong is education, which includesa quarterly newsletter and seminars at company headquarters andbranch offices.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   McAfee Associates (Products)Sun Life Assurance Company of Canada (Safety and securitymeasures).andO;Product:   Viruscan (Data security software) (Usage).andO;Topic:     SecurityData SecurityComputer CrimesComputer VirusesInsurance IndustryCompany ProfileRisk Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>